description:
Cellophane Bee (Colletes sp.), pollinating the last flowers of some Coast Buckwheat (Eriogonum latifolium) at Pescadero State Beach in coastal San Mateo County, CA. Tentative identification, based on the following characteristics [per the following reference: "Field Guide to the Common Bees of Californica," University of California Press, Berkeley, CA]: 

(1) Medium-sized bee, around half an inch long.
(2) Very hairy head and thorax. (Especially visible in Shots 2, 3, and 5).
(3) Pale bands of hair on the abdomen.
(4) Face that appears to taper towards the "chin."  (Most apparent in Shot 5.)
(5)  Eyes are slanted towards each other, making the head appear heart-shaped.  (Most apparent in Shot 5.)

Unfortunately, getting to species with Colletes bees is difficult at best.  The genus contains 31 different species just from California alone, and distinguishing one species from another requires inspecting the minutiae of their anatomy/morphology, which often means dissecting the insect. Therefore I am leaving this one at genus.

The females happen to sit in the mouth of the burrows when not out flying. It must have been a particularly tasty flower! This is the first of the two bees, which appears to be a Masked Bee (Hylaeus sp.). It reminds me of https://bugguide.net/node/view/924871/bgimage, which is Hylaeus polifolii, but I'm not sure these photos show enough to get a species ID on this one – I didn't get a clear shot of the face.
